            <div>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_zh_1">刻字應為「重」之異體。</note>
                <note type="ref" xml:id="note_zh_2">According to LF1, the characters 三世 are badly
                    damaged, though they were clearly traced out in the rubbings. All of the
                    transcriptions listed here read 三世, except Zhang1 who lists both characters as
                    illegible, and YH who transcribes 之業.</note>
                <note type="ref" xml:id="note_zh_3">Zhang1, Ki1 and YH read erroneously 峒峒. Ki2
                    transcribes 崆峒.</note>
                <note type="ref" xml:id="note_zh_4">嵿 is clearly seen in the rubbings. However,
                    nearly all transcriptions listed here read 嶺. The only exception is Zhang1 who
                    transcribes 頂. 萬嶺 is copiously documented in the classical texts.</note>
                <note type="ref" xml:id="note_zh_5">LT classifies the two characters as illegible.
                    YH transcribes 崔曉. 嶕嶢, meaning "high", should be correct.</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_zh_6">刻字似為「曰」。《儀禮》卷三十七〈士喪禮〉：「占曰某日從」，鄭注：「古文曰為日。」
                    又《吽迦陀野儀軌》上 (T #21, 1251:239c3-4)： 「汝曰曰與一百迦利沙波拏」 ； 《釋氏要覽》 (T #54,
                    2127:275b23)：「若有人能曰曰立要」 引文中「曰曰」當用為「日日」。</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_zh_7">石上刻字當為「儁」。「儁」與「雋」通，
                    見《康熙字典》頁一一八「儁」，一三六六「雋」；歐昌俊李海霞著《六朝唐五代石刻俗字研究》頁一零五。而「雋」可通用為「鎸」：《一切經音義》卷第五十六 (T #54,
                    2128:0683a18)：“「銘記—莫庭反謂雋刻金石以記功德也。” 」同書卷第五十四 (T #54,
                    2128:0667a16)：「“銘譽—莫庭反谓鎸刻金石以記功德者也。」”</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_zh_8">刻字應
                    為「王」，然「王」本古文「玉」字，參閱《康熙字典》頁七二七「王」。《說文解字》卷一上「玉」字形若今「王」字。《廣韻》：「［玉］ 說文本作王，隸加點以別王字。」</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_en_1">Of past, present, and future.</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_en_2">Literally, “Mt. Jishi.” As with the
                    following reference to Kongtong 崆峒, this seems both an indication of a specific
                    mountain range in what is now Gansu 甘肅 Province (the location of Binglingsi 炳靈寺,
                    near today’s Linxia 臨夏) and an evocation of a mythological and/or spiritual
                    state (cf. Zhang Zong 2000a, 70). See, as well, <hi rend="italic">Shijia
                    fangzhi</hi> 釋迦方志 (T #2088, 51:950a) for a discussion of the location of Mt.
                    Jishi relative to Mt. Kunlun 崑崘 and other legendary landmarks of the region.</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_en_3">The name for these mountains, and the
                    legends associated with them, echo the Kongtong 崆峒 mountains of the <hi rend="italic">Zhuangzi zaiyou</hi> 莊子在宥篇. The <hi rend="italic">Zhuangzi</hi> text relates that they were the site of a meeting between the
                    Yellow Emperor 黃帝 and the adept Guangcheng zi 廣成子, or the Master of Broad
                    Completion. The mountains in Gansu 甘肅, located in modern Pingliang, 平涼, were
                    later said to have been climbed by both Qin Shihuangdi 秦始皇帝 and Han Wudi 漢武帝,
                    and to have been the location of many numinous apparitions, such as purple mist.
                    See also Zhang Zong 2000a, 70.</note>
                <note type="display" xml:id="note_en_4">This is possibly a reference to the great
                    merit and spiritual benefits gained from reproducing Buddhist scriptures on
                    mountains (or anywhere else).</note>
            </div>
